-- Metals Gain on Stimulus Speculation: Commodities at Close
-- B y   C l a u d i a   C a r p e n t e r
-- 2012-09-03T16:54:30Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-09-03/metals-gain-on-stimulus-speculation-commodities-at-close.html
The UBS Bloomberg CMCI  index  of 26
raw materials was up 0.4 percent at 1,608.436 at 5:50 p.m. in
 London .  BASE METALS  Copper rose in London as contracting Chinese manufacturing
fueled speculation about economic stimulus in the world’s
biggest consumer of the metal.  Copper for three-month delivery added 0.7 percent to $7,671
a metric ton by 5:28 p.m. on the LME, nearing its 100-day moving
average and extending August’s 0.7 percent increase. Copper for
December delivery rose 0.8 percent to $3.4845 a pound on the
Comex in New York, where floor trading was closed today for the
Labor Day holiday.  Base metals markets: NI BMMKTS  PRECIOUS METALS  Gold is poised to advance on speculation central banks may
do more to spur growth, potentially boosting demand for the
metal as a protection of wealth. Silver gained to the highest
level since April.  December-delivery gold rose 0.3 percent to $1,693.30 an
ounce in electronic trading on the Comex by 9:55 a.m. in  New
York , where floor trading is closed for the Labor Day holiday.
Immediate-delivery gold was little changed at $1,692.07 an ounce
in London, after earlier climbing to $1,693.03, the highest
price since March 27.  Silver for December delivery gained as much as 1.6 percent
to $31.935 an ounce, the most expensive since April 20, and was
last at $31.870.  Platinum for October delivery gained 0.7 percent to
$1,548.90 an ounce and palladium for December delivery advanced
0.5 percent to $632.50 an ounce.  Precious metals: NI PCMKTS  CRUDE OIL  Oil rose on speculation central banks will take more steps
to boost growth after manufacturing unexpectedly contracted in
 China .  Crude for October delivery increased 48 cents, or 0.5
percent, to $96.95 a barrel at 12:19 p.m. in electronic trading
on the  New York Mercantile Exchange . Earlier, it touched $96.96,
the highest intraday level since Aug. 27. Prices have climbed 25
percent since reaching the year’s low of $77.28 on June 28. They
advanced 9.6 percent in August, a second monthly gain.  Brent oil for October settlement rose $1.38, or 1.2
percent, to $115.95 a barrel on the London-based ICE Futures
Europe exchange. Prices advanced 9.2 percent last month. The
European benchmark grade’s premium to West Texas Intermediate
was at $19.14, compared with $18.10 on Aug. 31.  Oil markets: NI OILMARKET  NATURAL GAS  U.K. natural gas prices surged as flows from the South Hook
liquefied gas terminal in  Wales  slumped while Statoil ASA was
scheduled to halt the largest North Sea field for planned
maintenance this month.  Within-day gas jumped as much as 3.9 pence to 61.3 pence a
therm and was at 60.6 pence at 4:36 p.m. London time, according
to broker data compiled by Bloomberg. Today’s high price is the
most since May 4 and equal to $9.63 a million British thermal
units. A therm is 100,000 Btu.  U.K. natural gas: NI NUKMKT
Gas market: NI GASMARKET
Americas natural gas: NI AGASMARKET
European natural gas: NI EGASMARKET  GRAINS, OILSEEDS  Wheat slipped for a second day in Paris on reduced concern
that  Russia , the world’s third-biggest exporter of the grain
last season, may curb cereal shipments after a drought cut
production.  Milling wheat for November delivery fell as much as 0.7
percent to 262 euros ($329.31) a metric ton before trading at
263.50 euros by 3:22 p.m. on NYSE Liffe in the French capital.
The Chicago Board of Trade is closed today for the Labor Day
holiday.  Grain markets: NI GRMKTS  SOFT COMMODITIES  Cocoa declined in London as a three-month rally may have
been overdone as speculation of dry weather in West Africa has
yet to materialize. Coffee advanced.  Cocoa for December delivery dropped 1.3 percent to 1,675
pounds ($2,661) a metric ton by 2:08 p.m. in London on NYSE
Liffe. White, or refined, sugar declined 0.5 percent to $555
a ton and robusta coffee gained 0.4 percent to $2,086 a ton.  Soft  commodities markets : NI SOMKTS  European Carbon Permits  European Union carbon permits for December jumped 2.2
percent to 8.26 euros a metric ton on the ICE Futures Europe
exchange, the highest since July 5.  EU Carbon Emissions: NI ECBMKT  OIL PRODUCTS  European naphtha advanced as four cargoes changed hands.
Total SA bought two shipments of ultra-low sulfur diesel, while
Morgan Stanley purchased barges of the fuel for at least the
10th session.  Gasoline extended gains to trade at the highest price in
more than four months as  Brent crude  rose.  The 12,500 metric-ton naphtha cargoes traded from $989 to
$1,000 a ton, according to a survey of traders and brokers
monitoring the Platts pricing window. That’s up from a deal at
$983 on Aug. 31. Vitol Group, Royal Dutch Shell Plc, BASF SE and
BP Plc were the buyers. Trafigura Beheer BV sold for a second
session, while BP also sold.  Oil Products Europe: NI OPEMKT
Gasoline: NI GASOLINE
Heating oil: NI HEATOIL  To contact the reporter on this story:
